@node ABOUT "About"
pciparallel.device is a device driver for PCI parallel port cards in an
Elbox Mediator. Uses IO ports only so should work on all Mediators

Supports cards with 1 and 2 ports on. Currently supports use of 1 or 2
printers and 1 Parallel Zip drive.

The Zip drives passthrough can be used to connect a printer.

Code for interfacing with the mediator is my own, as is the printer parallel
code, Zip drive support is based on 'ppazip.device' by Bruce Abbot.

I've made a number of changes to Bruce's code including:

Replacing statically declared message ports and IO requests with calls to
Exec CreateMsgPort/CreateIORequest.

Reducing the timer device overhead, Bruce was calling FindTask for each time
the Timer was used for a delay, which could only happen from within our task.

Replaced time delays in PutByte/GetByte with handshaking code, the device
should be a little faster now, and more compatable with 040/060 systems.

@endnode
@node REQUIREMENTS "Requirements"
To use pciparallel.device you will need:

An Amiga (!) with a correctly installed Mediator, should work with any model.
pci.library v4 or better.
A PC parallel port card.
Something to connect to the parallel port might be helpful.
@endnode
@node INSTALLATION "Installation"
Due to the number of different parallel cards around there is a little work
to do to install this device.

The device opens the file ENV:Mediator/IOConfig and reads this for a list of
devices to search for.

I've added a couple but I expect there are many others not listed.

To add yours add a new line with:

Vendor Device IOSpace(x)=Parallel/Config/EPPOnly/Unused ...

For Vendor and Device use 4 digits hex, no leading 0x or $ IOSpace(x) can be
worked out from your PCIInfo output.

IOSpace(x)= tells the device what kind of IO registers exist on the memory range:

Parallel is for SPP registers.
Config is the additional registers used by ECP ports (mostly for configuring modes
hence the name)
EPPOnly is SPP register map but without corresponding config range.
Serial - Reisters for a 16450 UART (Unused by pciparallel)
Unused - No Registers or unknown function.

Parallel and EPPOnly ranges will be 8 bytes, Config will be 4 or 8. Unfortunately
serial ranges also seem to be 8 byte. Some experimentation may be rquired.

Here are a couple of examples (both tested cards from config file):

Pci Device 3:
   VendorID: $9710
   VendorName: MosChip Semiconductor Technology
   DeviceID: $9835
   DeviceName: 9865 2 serial, 1 LPT port PCI Card
   ClassCode: $78000
   RevisionID: $1
   InterruptPin: 3
   SubsystemVendorID: $1000
   SubsystemID: $12
   IOSpace0: $eb6800 - $eb6807
   IOSpace1: $eb6c00 - $eb6c07
   IOSpace2: $eb7000 - $eb7007
   IOSpace3: $eb7400 - $eb7407
   IOSpace4: $eb7800 - $eb7807
   IOSpace5: $eb7c00 - $eb7c0f

This card has vendor $9710 device $9835, 2x serial 1x parallel ports on,
serial are IOSpace0,1 SPP Registers are IOSpace2 and ECR config registers
are IOSpace3, (from chipset docs)

So config line becomes:

9710 9835 IOSpace0=Serial IOSpace1=Serial IOSpace2=Parallel IOSpace3=Config IOSpace4=Unused IOSpace5=Unused

(Note MUST be all one line, newlines are used as a device separator)

Pci Device 5:
   VendorID: $1407
   VendorName: Lava Computer MFG Inc.
   DeviceID: $8000
   DeviceName: Lava Parallel
   ClassCode: $70101
   RevisionID: $0
   InterruptPin: 4
   SubsystemVendorID: $0
   SubsystemID: $0
   IOSpace0: $eb6c00 - $ea6c07

This one has just one I/O range, as it is only an EPP port, so config line is:

1407 8000 IOSpace0=EppOnly IOSpace1=unused IOSpace2=unused IOSpace3=unused IOSpace4=unused IOSace5=unused

You don't actualy need to enter all IOSpace ranges, if your card has only
2 ranges you can enter just those. The config range will be the higher numbered of
the two.

Once you've adjusted the file save it in sys:prefs/env-archive/Mediator
as IOConfig
(If you are still not sure ask on the Mediator Yahoo group.)

Then copy the file pciparallel.device to devs:

If you have a Zip drive you can copy the ZIP and ZIC mountfiles to
devs:DosDrivers (or Storage if you don't want them always mounted)

Note: If you use pciserial.device from Matthew Allatt the config file is the same.
(This is intentional)

@endnode
@node USAGE "Usage"
To use a zip drive just double click on the supplied DOSDrivers or put them in
devs:dosdrivers to have them mounted at start up

ZIP is for Amiga formatted disks,
ZIC is for PC Formatted disks.

Disks are fully compatable with ppazip formatted disks.

Disks can be protected with Zip Tools as supplied with WB, Zip tools will
detect pciparallel.device once it is mounted. pciparallel.device recognises
write protection, read/write protection (as write protection) and will allow
writing to a disk that has been temporarily write enabled. To write protect
a temporarily enabled disk, you must eject it from your ZIP drive. Changes
to the protection status of mounted disks will be detected, but you may have
to wait for up to 6 seconds for the change to appear.


To use a printer select 'use custom device' in Printer Prefs
click the popup gadget and select 'pciparallel.device' from the list. (If it
isn't listed see @{"here" link "INSTALLATION"} )

Select unit 0 for single port cards, and unit 1 for second port on 2 port cards
(But see @{"here" link "BUGS"} for a couple of problems to be aware of.)
@endnode
@node BUGS "Bugs"
There are a few problems you should be aware of.

If you have a printer attached to a Zip drive passthrough the device shares
hardware between the printer and Zip drive, so while one device is active
the other must wait, normally this isn't a problem, but if you try to print
to a port with just a Zip drive attached the print request will wait for
ever for the printer to be ready, and the Zip will be locked out. You should be
able to cancel the print request, but it will take a few minutes to respond.
(and I'm not 100% sure my AbortIO code works fully)

While the device supports 2 port cards, it does not support 2 zip drives due
to some static data used in the device structure. I could probably fix this
if anyone really needed it.

Only a ppa Zip Drive is supported, Zip Plus and Zip250PP are not.

There is code to read data from a printer using nibble mode, however this has
only been briefly tested.

For some reason trying to open the additional info window in Scout causes a
crash (devices->pciparallel.device then click on more) Don't understand why.

@endnode
@node HISTORY "History"
This is a brief and probably not very accurate history for pciparallel.device

28/07/02        v0.1        First actually working version, very basic but can
                            be used to print. Doesn't implement all parallel.device
                            options yet.

13/08/02                    Started adding support for 2 ports (firstly 2 devices)

                v0.2        2 ports driven from one device.
                            Added PARB_SHARED support.

08/10/02        v0.3        Name changed to pciparallel.device.
                            Added PARB_EOF mode support (I hope)

17/02/03        v0.4        Tried using an interrupt to reduce CPU overhead.

11/02/04        v0.5        Returned to PIO as the interrupt code was not always
                            successful, and is reported not to work in the bottom
                            two slots in a 1200SX
                            Started adding reads.

                v0.6        Internal unreleased version.

01/10/08        v0.7a       Started to work on Zip driver (from ppazip.device by
                            Bruce Abbot)

11/04/09        v0.7b       Standalone ZIP version. Some code improvements, using
                            Exec to allocate IOReqs and MP's, and no longer
                            calling FindTask when setting up timer.device calls
                            (wasn't required, only called from task code)
12/04/09                    Removed time delays from putbyte and getbyte and
                            replaced them with REQ handshaking, which is available
                            on full PC parallel ports. This has made the device a
                            little faster, and hopefully made it more compatible
                            with fast 040/060 systems.
                            Removed 10ms delay added by Bruce as I'm hoping my putbyte/
                            getbyte changes will have fixed this.
16/04/09                    Fixed register mixup in SCSI-Direct/time delay - SCSI
                            direct now works, the device no longer crashes HDToolbox.
22/04/09                    Started to merge pciparallel.device code, to produce single
                            combined device driver.
01/05/09                    Finally got combine version to work, was using movea instead
                            of movea.l in some places. Some more work to do.
                            Found out how to switch the Zip in and out of passthrough
                            mode, added this to connect and disconnect routines, mixed
                            mode usage works very nicely now.
02/05/09                    Mostly works, fixed unit numbers in open routime, still
                            problems aborting parallel printouts when no printer attached.
04/05/09        v0.8        Hopefully fixed aborting when no printer attached.

                            First Aminet release.

14/05/09        v0.9        Fixed bit values while printing, was reading a doc that was
                            wrong. Fixed status return - YAM no longer complains before
                            printing
25/05/09                    Finaly debugged the Nibble mode code, and got the printer to
                            respond to a read request
01/10/09                    Corrected small bug in diskchange code. Changed Test Unit
                            Ready to a mode sense during dischange int code to find disk
                            protect status - needs some more work yet. Added some changes
                            to driver to support this.
24/10/09                    Finaly worked out the commands needed to check for disk write
                            protection (Not mode sense - vendor specific)
                            Added detection of this, along with checking for temporary
                            write enabling. Added a patch to force a diskchange int, as
                            otherwise WB can't see changes made to the protection status.
                            This may cause slowdowns of disk mounting.

                            Second Aminet release.

30/01/10                    Added back Bruce's 10ms delay, seems it is needed after all!
                            Inlined the getblock and putblock code.
31/01/10                    Fixed the NSDDevQuery command code, changed diskchange timer
                            to use UNIT_VBLANK rather than UNIT_MICROHZ
03/01/10        v0.10       Slightly inreased the delay at the beginning of my 10ms replacement
                            code, tidied up code a little, use 020 code where possible.

                            Third Aminet release.

27/02/10                    Changed the bit settings in the disconnect routine, to prevent
                            Epson printers resetting themselves on each ZIP command.
23/03/10        v0.11       Fixed bug in init code that was causing my printer to hang on first
                            Printout after power up.

                            Fourth Aminet release.

04/02/11                    Added support for LAVA EPP only Parallel port cards.
09/02/11                    Removed some handshaking code in byte read and write routines.
18/02/11        v0.12       Some more '020 optimisations

                            Fifth Aminet release

@endnode
